As earthworm effects on plants could be mediated via changes in soil abiotic and biotic conditions, we explored soil nutrient concentrations and microbial properties. Overall, 
 t-test results showed that the presence of earthworms did not affect soil basal respiration (Df = 10; 
 t = 0; 
 p = 1), microbial biomass (Df = 10; 
 t = −0.34; 
 p = 0.74), microbial specific respiratory quotient (Df = 10; 
 t = 1.17; 
 p = 0.27), water content (Df = 10; 
 t = 0.59; 
 p = 0.57), and nutrient content (Carbon: Df = 10; 
 t = −0.11; 
 p = 0.92; Nitrogen: Df = 10; 
 t = −0.54; 
 p = 0.60 and C/N ratio: Df = 10; 
 t = 0.88; 
 p = 0.40). The microbial community structure was also not significantly affected by the presence of earthworms (Df = 1; 
 F = 1.48; 
 p = 0.41).
